Crimea and Sudetes, same fight?
BRUSSELS - The Russian takeover of Crimea constitutes the most serious example of peacetime aggression that Europe has experienced since the annexation of the Sudetes by Nazi Germany in 1938.
It is certainly today customary to downplay the importance of the "Munich lessons" when referring to this episode in which Neville Chamberlain and Édouard Daladier gave in to Hitler's demands regarding Czechoslovakia in order to pacify the Führer.
Nevertheless, if the Western world were to turn a blind eye to the annexation of Crimea - the second case of invasion of a sovereign territory by Russian President Vladimir Putin, after the takeover of the Georgian regions of Abkhazia and South Ossetia in 2008 - today's democratic leaders might greatly regret their inaction.
Within Western capitals, reactions have thus far been mixed.
The sanctions currently under consideration - such as expulsion from the G8 - might seem laughable if the threat to peace in Europe were not so serious.
Putin considers the collapse of the Soviet Union as the greatest catastrophe of modern times, the man relentlessly striving to resurrect a fallen Russian empire.
If the West is to be taken seriously, it will have to act with the same determination displayed by Putin.
The many successes of the Russian president within the framework of his imperialist project have thus far cost him almost nothing.
His initiative in favor of a Eurasian Economic Community has enabled Russia to bring a number of resource-rich states into its fold, such as Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, and Turkmenistan.
Georgia was dismembered in 2008.
As for the Armenian government, Russian intimidation has pushed it to reject the association agreement proposed by the European Union.
And here is the most precious geostrategic trophy of all - Ukraine - which could well fall into Putin's hands.
Without Ukraine, Russia "ceases to be an empire," as explained by former U.S. National Security Advisor Zbigniew Brzezinski; "on the contrary, with a bribed and then subordinated Ukraine, Russia automatically becomes an empire again." And since the vast majority of Ukrainians have no desire whatsoever to join Putin's empire, it is highly likely that the country ruled by the Russian president will now become a highly militarized state, a sort of Soviet Union without a Communist Party.
It is essential that the international community's response be commensurate with the level of adventurism displayed by Putin.
Canceling summits, proposing trade agreements, and participating in forums as unproductive as the G8 will not be enough.
Only measures involving the imposition of tangible economic sanctions, capable of affecting Russian citizens—who, let us recall, continue to re-elect Putin to power—will allow us to hope to see the Kremlin abandon its expansionist course.
What sanctions could they be?
First, Turkey could decide to close the Bosporus Strait to Russian transports, as it did after the Russo-Georgian War of 2008.
At the time, Turkey had blocked access to the Black Sea in order to prevent the United States from intervening, although it now clearly appears that this was not the intention of the U.S.
Today, Turkey could choose to close the Turkish straits not only to Russian warships, but also to all commercial vessels heading to Russian ports in the Black Sea.
The impact on Russia's economy—as well as on Putin's military ambitions—would be considerable.
Turkey is authorized to close the Dardanelles under an amendment made in 1982 to the 1936 Montreux Convention.
Turkey could thus turn against Putin the very motive he invoked to justify the annexation of Crimea—that is, that he would protect the Russian ethnic groups living there—by asserting itself as protecting its Turkish cousins of Tatar origin, who, given the mistreatment they have suffered at the hands of Russia, clearly wish to remain under Ukrainian rule.
This week, Turkish Foreign Minister Ahmet Davutoğlu ordered his plane to turn back mid-air in order to head to Kiev to provide support to the new interim government.
Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdoğan, who, as Putin knows, is not exactly a softie, could thus follow suit by immediately closing the Turkish straits to Russian transports—until Putin recalls all his troops from Crimea so they can return to their bases, namely those of Sebastopol or Russia.
It would be good for Turkey to be able to rely on the guarantee provided by Article 5 of the NATO treaty in case Russia were to try to intimidate it.
Secondly, U.S. President Barack Obama could impose the same type of financial sanctions against Russia that he imposed on Iran regarding its nuclear program.
These sanctions have indeed significantly undermined Iran's economy.
In the same way, refusing access to the American financial system for all banks doing business with Russian banks or companies would generate an unprecedented economic chaos in Russia since the fall of communism.
Russian citizens must understand that allowing Putin—whose rise to power is based on his promise to end the shortages of the early post-Soviet era—to continue his aggressive imperialist agenda could cost them dearly.
Thirdly, it would be possible for Obama to remind the Chinese of their role in Eurasian stability.
A true tragedy in Putin's eyes, the disintegration of the Soviet Union represented for China the most formidable geostrategic windfall one can imagine.
In an instant, this empire that had seized millions of hectares of Chinese territory over the centuries, and threatened the People's Republic with nuclear annihilation, simply vanished.
Since then, the independent states of Central Asia, and Ukraine itself, have become important trading partners of China.
Russia's invasion of Georgia seriously upset China, as was evident during the Shanghai Cooperation Organization summit held in the aftermath of the war (this regional grouping comprising a number of former Soviet states with common borders with China and the motherland).
Russia tried to get the OSCE to recognize the independence of Abkhazia and South Ossetia.
The Organization however expressed its disagreement.
Or, the Central Asian member countries - Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, and Uzbekistan - would never have been able to stand up to the Kremlin without China's support.
It now falls to Chinese President Xi Jinping to be less enigmatic in his response to Putin's boldness.
The true test of this Chinese claim to be a genuine and responsible protagonist within the international community will indeed take place very soon at the United Nations.
Will China support this manifest violation of international law committed by Putin, or will it stand in support of Ukraine's territorial integrity?
Two other sanction options are also conceivable.
Each Russian leader could thus see their visas denied or canceled.
It would also be possible to freeze a number of assets, particularly those that have been laundered by oligarchs close to Putin.
It is only when the pain becomes unbearable, and particularly for the elites, that this kind of struggle that Putin is waging today could fail.
The price of inaction could well prove to be considerable.
Many countries, from Japan to Israel, rely on America's promise to act firmly against any serious threat to peace.
Furthermore, when Ukraine gave up its nuclear arsenal in 1994, it did so on the express condition that the United States (alongside the United Kingdom, France, and Russia) guarantee its territorial integrity.
If Crimea were to remain annexed, no one could blame Ukraine if it decided to renuclearize its defense (something it remains technologically capable of doing).
When Chamberlain returned from Munich, Winston Churchill addressed him with the famous phrase, "You had the choice between war and dishonor."
You have chosen dishonor, and you will have war." Obama and other Western leaders are today faced with a similar choice.
If they were to choose dishonor, we can be certain that the audacious Putin will eventually serve them a new war.
